Full(-ish) list of changes:\
\
\ul Book Names\ulnone \
Originally, I had changed all the acquisition messages to reflect what each book is, which is something that seems to have started with the MS-DOS/Apple II GS versions. However, the original game does actually support separate names for each of them, yet chose to say refer to each simply as \'93Book of Ys\'94, so I thought more about why that might be, and it would seem that most people cannot read these books, so it stands to reason that Adol would not know which book he is getting, at least until he has the glasses. More about the books \
\
\ul Character Names\ulnone \
Rhea vs Reah (vs Lair (vs Leia)) vs Rea - While I think variations of this are about equal chances of whether or not the reader will know the intended pronunciation (except \'93Leia\'94, which would be much less likely to be mispronounced since one of the most popular characters in 20th century American cinema shares that name), the character has already been firmly established with an \'91R\'92, and it\'92s certainly worth mentioning that \'91Rhea\'92 is the \'93Mother of gods\'94 in Greek mythology, which makes \'91Rhea\'92 seem to be the most appropriate choice. In the prototype, Rhea was named Koruberiasu (
\f1 \'a5\'b3\'a5\'eb\'a5\'d9\'a5\'ea\'a5\'a2\'a5\'b9
\f0 ; perhaps a parody of Golvellius). \
\
Dabii - To me, \'93Dabii\'94 more closely resembles the Japanese pronunciation, as \'93Dabbie\'94 looks like it\'92s meant to be pronounced \'93Dab-bee\'94. I had also considered if this might have been intended to be a variation of \'91David\'92, which doesn\'92t seem to be the case, so \'93Dabii\'94 seems to be the \'93true name\'94 because the \'91\'97\'91 character extends the pronunciation slightly.\
\
Raaba - I didn\'92t really change this - the \'91\'97\'91 in his Japanese name indicates the vowel sound before it should extend a bit, and like with Dabii, I wanted the spelling to better reflect the pronunciation of the name, which I feel is especially important with this character as his name is a pun: \'93Raaba, the Robber\'94. \
\
Luta - This may seem like it should be \'91Luther\'92, however, I believe this name, like the aforementioned Raaba, is another pun: \'93Luta, the Looter\'94 (though he is not explicitly mentioned to be one of Goban\'92s thieves, I think it\'92s likely that either he is one of them, or was planned to be when the name was chosen).\
\
Bhajju - Wait - WHO!? \
Well, the development process changed a lot of things since it started, but in the actual retail demo disk, one of the townspeople (who you can\'92t normally speak to, because the game doesn\'92t give the player control to allow it) mentions the two trees each by name, so I thought it was a a fun callback to include this reference.\
\
Zepik Mayor - He is never named in the original versions - this was an invention that Eternal introduced, and since he plays no role in the story after this and is never mentioned by name (including in Dawn of Ys, which does actually include him as an NPC), I decided not to include the \'93new\'94 name. In the prototype he is actually Jeba\'92s character (and I believe still nameless).\
\
\ul Item/Equipment Names\ulnone \
The names of these don\'92t really fit well with everything else, so they\'92ve been updated to fit within the parameters of everything else.\
\
SMALL-SHIELD - The icons suggest this shield is non-metal (possibly wood), and the dialog states its a starter/beginner\'92s shield, so this is now the \'91Wood Shield\'92.\
\
MIDDLE-SHIELD - Since it\'92s not apparent what level of metallurgy is available to Esterians, I didn\'92t want to assume the production of steel, so I figured an \'91Iron Shield\'92 was the next reasonable one (especially considering the silver mine is now closed). The blueish hue does seem compatible with iron.\
\
LARGE-SHIELD - Again, not wanting to assume too much, but the trim of the shield seems like it could be bronze, and bronze is an alloy that could be used to make a harder shield than iron. \
\
RING-MAIL - It does sound kind of cool, but it doesn\'92t fit the name scheme of all the other rings, so it was adjusted to \'91Shield Ring\'92 (which I think fits better for anyone who already has played any RPGs to automatically be familiar with).\
\
Roda Seed - This is not changed; I\'92m only pointing it out because the icon on every version is not one that I think looks like a \'93seed\'94 (the MSX version even looks more like a bag full of orange fruit), but I did make sure to ask Hiromasa Iwasaki (who led the development on the PC Engine remake and is one of the top 3 knowledgable people on Ys in the world) about this to confirm that \'93seed\'94 is indeed the correct word to be using. He remarked that when he was working on it, he noted the graphic does not match but also chose to stay true to the original words; I felt it important I did the same in this spot. \
\
\'93Jade\'94 Key - The Japanese text translates to \'93Passage Key\'94, but you need two keys to make it through said passage. Jade and Ivory are a somewhat popular jewelry combination, and since the two keys seem to be a set and this one is green, Jade seemed a much more appropriate name. \
\
\ul Silver / Cleria\ulnone  \
One of the bigger problems with translating the script is understanding whether or not silver and Cleria are the same thing, or just look alike. I discussed this with Hiromasa Iwasaki in detail to decide what to do, which is treat it that Cleria looks like silver, and therefore since nobody knows the story of Cleria, they just think it\'92s \'93better\'94 silver. \
\
According to Iwasaki, the reason there aren\'92t things like \'93Clerian forks\'94 being found is that when they buried it, it diminished. Without the presence of sunlight or magic, it can\'92t remain. This is why the shops were able to have it in the first place, and also how Silver Sword can remain intact, because it is at the base of the Roda Tree (Bhajju). It can also be speculated that perhaps the purity of Cleria can also make a difference.\
\
In the prototype, the sword was originally the Platinum Sword, and the Silver Armor/Shield was \'91Mystic\'92.\
\
\ul Locations / Historic Names\ulnone \
Dahm vs Darm - The Japanese text is 
\f1 \'a5\'c0
\f0 \'97
\f1 \'a5\'e0
\f0  (Daamu), and the Japanese version of Chronicles romanizes this as \'93Dahm\'94 (Fun Fact: \'93Fact\'94 is \'93Fukt\'94 in that same version), which in my opinion is the closest match to the Japanese pronunciation. I feel that it\'92s phonetic similarities to \'93Damn/Damned\'94 is something that played a factor into the name, so I felt it especially important to preserve its original pronunciation (I\'92m not really sure where they got the \'91r\'92 from in the first place).\
\
Rado's Spire vs Lado Tower -  This area was partially based on the north tower in Lupin III: Castle of Cagliostro. The name 
\f1 \'a5\'e9\'a5\'c9 (Rado) has the same syllable count as \'b1\'b1 (Kita
\f0 ), so the rhythm of pronunciation seems somewhat similar to calling it \'91The Tower of Lado\'92. However, I feel that referring to it as a \'91tower\'92 when you\'92re already in a \'91tower\'92 doesn\'92t really give the best sense of how to envision the things we can\'92t see to the player. For several different reasons, I feel that \'91Spire\'92 is very compatible here. Although I cited the Japanese romanization for the previous example, Japanese doesn\'92t distinguish \'91R\'92 from \'91L\'92 and in this case \'91Rado\'92 feels a bit more natural to say in English, IMHO.\
\
Solomon vs Salmon - As phonetics have played a significant factor in several things so far, I think the extra syllable you get from transliterating to 'Solomon' is more along the lines of the intention of Hashimoto-sama.\
\
